    <h2>What to Ask a Bakery Equipment Dealer</h2>
    <p>Most bakery owners, especially first-time buyers, don't ask enough questions. Here's the complete list of questions you should ask before committing to any purchase:</p>

    <h3>About the Equipment</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>"Is this the current model or an outgoing model?"</strong> Dealers sometimes discount last year's model without telling you. Know what you're buying.</li>
      <li><strong>"What is the warranty period and what does it cover?"</strong> Standard warranties are typically 1 year on parts and labour. Some brands offer 2 years. Know what's excluded (heating elements, wear parts, damage from improper use).</li>
      <li><strong>"What's the energy consumption rating?"</strong> Ask for the kW rating on electric equipment. High energy consumption adds significantly to operating costs.</li>
      <li><strong>"What are the installation requirements?"</strong> Electrical load, gas connection specs, ventilation needs, floor load — get these in writing so you can prepare your kitchen.</li>
      <li><strong>"Do you have this model in stock or is it made-to-order?"</strong> Lead times for made-to-order equipment can be 4–12 weeks. Know this upfront.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>About After-Sales Support</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>"Do you have a service centre in my city?"</strong> Don't accept "we have a service partner" — ask for the name, address, and contact number of the service centre.</li>
      <li><strong>"What is the average response time for a service call?"</strong> A reasonable answer is 24–48 hours for in-city service. More than that is a red flag.</li>
      <li><strong>"Are spare parts available locally or do they need to be imported?"</strong> Imported spare parts can take 4–8 weeks. For critical equipment, this is a significant business risk.</li>
      <li><strong>"Do you offer AMC (Annual Maintenance Contract)?"</strong> A good AMC covers preventive maintenance visits, priority service calls, and discounted spare parts. Ask for the AMC pricing upfront.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>About the Dealer</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>"Are you an authorised dealer/distributor for this brand?"</strong> Ask to see the authorisation certificate. Buying from non-authorised dealers often voids the manufacturer's warranty.</li>
      <li><strong>"Can you provide references from other bakeries in my city that use this equipment?"</strong> A good dealer should be able to provide 2–3 references. Follow up and actually call them.</li>
      <li><strong>"What is your GST number and trade registration?"</strong> Always get a proper GST invoice — it's required for input tax credit and is evidence that you're dealing with a legitimate business.</li>
    </ul>

